article.description:
Ann Wauters tied a career high with 20 points,
and Becky Hammon added 17 and a season-high nine assists for the Liberty.
article.headline: NY defeats Silver Stars for the 6th straight time
article.linkText: Liberty prevails as Silver Stars go 0-6 on road
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Liberty made quick work of the
last-place San Antonio Silver Stars.

Ann Wauters tied a career high with 20 points, and Becky Hammon
added 17 and a season-high nine assists to lead the Liberty to a
77-59 victory over the Silver Stars on Tuesday night.

"Becky found me perfectly today," Wauters said. "I can't
remember how many times she gave me (the ball) perfect in my hands
that I just had to throw it in the basket."

Shameka Christon added 14 points and Elena Baranova grabbed 10
rebounds for the Liberty (5-4), winners of three straight and four
of their last five. New York led by 14 at halftime, and by at least
11 after the break.

"I think we're beginning to understand we need everyone," New
York coach Pat Coyle said. "Elena only had three points, but she
had 10 rebounds. I thought she did a pretty good job defending.
Crystal (Robinson) did an unbelievable job defending Marie
Ferdinand. They understand their roles. Some nights they have it
going on, but every night they're out there defending."

Chantelle Anderson and Ferdinand scored 14 points apiece for San
Antonio (2-10), which lost its fourth straight. Ferdinand shot just
3-for-14 from the field, but was 8-for-8 on free throws.

The Silver Stars are last in the Western Conference, and only
Charlotte (1-8) has a worse record.

"I've seen them on tape against just about everybody they've
played," Coyle said of San Antonio. "All the players see the
record, and I was more concerned about the effort and the focus."

The Silver Stars dropped to 0-6 on the road in the opener of a
four-game trip. They also began a stretch in which they play seven
of 10 away from home.

New York beat the San Antonio franchise for the sixth straight
time -- including 4-0 since the Silver Stars moved from Utah before
the 2003 season.

"You can't take any team in this league for granted," Hammon
said. "Everybody has solid players. We've come in the last few
games with the mind-set the last few games that it's not about who
we're playing, but it's about us. Lately, we've been executing well
in the offensive end. We're getting nice looks for people and
people are starting to knock them down.

Wauters helped New York get off to a strong start, scoring six
points in the first 4½ minutes as the Liberty took a 14-6 lead.

Shyra Ely's jumper cut San Antonio's deficit to 26-22 with 7:23
remaining in the period, before the Liberty went on a 16-4 run over
a 5-minute stretch to push their lead to 42-26 in the final minute.

San Antonio cut its deficit to 11 twice in the second half -- the
last on rookie Katie Feenstra's layup that trimmed New York's lead
to 53-42 near the midpoint of the period.

La'Keshia Frett's jumper with 53.7 seconds left gave the Liberty
their biggest lead of the game at 77-57.

"We played much better in the second half," Silver Stars coach
Dan Hughes said. "There weren't many bright spots in the first
half. Becky Hammon really created so much action with the ball,
that drew us into a helpless situation."

Wauters, who shot 9-for-16 and also grabbed eight rebounds, had
her highest total since also scoring 20 against Utah on June 30,
2002, while playing for the defunct Cleveland Rockers. She came
close to breaking the mark in two of the last three games,
finishing with 19 each time.

Coyle credited Wauters' improvement to her work with assistant
coach Marianne Stanley.

"She works everyday with Marianne," Coyle said. "She comes in
45 minutes early and they work on stuff, and you can see the fruits
of their labor. She gets better everyday."

The game was a reunion for Wauters and Hughes, who were together
in Cleveland from 2000-03.

"I talked with him before the game," Wauters said. "It was
nice seeing him. He's the one who drafted me, so he knows me."

Wauters and Hammon each scored 12 points in the first half to
help the Liberty build a 44-30 advantage at the break.

The Liberty shot 52 percent (17-for-33) in the first half,
while limiting the Silver Stars to 33 percent (10-for-30).
